title: Star progressive loading machines and accessories
postcontent: If someone wants to get into heavy production of ammo but can't afford a fully automatic machine, even if one were for sale on the market, this is the next best thing.  Star progressive loaders perform all the steps of the reloading process in one stroke of a lever.  some folks have even operated the lever by foot with additional linkages.  The operator just stands there and introduces the bullet each stroke.  The primers, powder and cartridge cases are all introduced automatically.  If there is an assistant, perhaps a spouse, the magazines of primers and other components can be fed into the operation as needed.  Each individual  basic machine costs over a thousand.  Then there are additional dies for various calibers, spare  parts that wear faster than others, and other supporting equipment.   In all, a person winds up with just over 2 thousand per machine.  That's where I am now.  I load for .38/.357, 9mm, 10mm, .44, 45/45acp.  I can even set up two machines to produce the same caliber when the added volume is needed, provided there is someone there to run it.  So, there you have it.  Since it is not fully automatic, it costs less than an automatic machine.    However, it is much more flexible than a fully automatic machine.  These machines have been produced by Star for at least 40 years.  They are reliable and stout.  The company still produces them.  The demand for these will continue to grow as long as those who believe in the Second Amendment hunker down for what is inevitable under Democratic domination.  Check the shelves at most retailers - there is no ammo gathering dust.  So there you have it.  Because of my age and other activities I am getting out of this business.  If a person isn't going to have around 10  thousand for this equipment, powder, primers, cases and bullets, then they need not entertain any thoughts of getting into this business.  The start up cost is high.  The margin of  profit is becoming huge.  The demand for 9mm alone would  return many times the investment.  As I said "serious reloading."   Not for the week end plinker.  If we get together I can discuss powder, primers, cases and bullets.

This course is designed for a wide range of students; from someone who has never touched a firearm before, to the very experienced shooter.

title: forster 308 nato headspace guage
postcontent: this is a forster headspace guage for checking the safety of rifles with nato 762x51 chambers. the chamber on a nato rifle IS NOT the same dimension as 308 winchester though the ammo will chamber in both rifles. this guage checks the maximum safe headspace on nato chambers--a military rifle that will swallow a 308 winchester field guage may be perfectly ok when checked with the proper nato guage. an easy and cheap way to check rifles at gun shows etc to ensure they are in proper specs before buying and firing.

title: Sako Barreled actions and premium stocks
postcontent:
I have 9 of these.  They are the original line of action sizes known as Vixen, Finnbear, etc  I also have several semi-inletted stocks, both traditional and thumbhole.   I have had these for nearly 40 years.  If you are serious about building a custom rifle, this is a rare opportunity.  There are plenty of current actions available but these sakos are rare.  A finely finished rifle can be worth many thousands of dollars.  Not for the beginner.  I have some cheap stocks for  someone who wants to get started.
All nine of my Sako barreled actions are "Pre-70"  These are the  premium run of Sakos.  There is a 25% reduction for post '70 Sakos.

In the long action, L61R,  I have the following

.338 mag, magnaported , 24", standard barrel weight,  SN 64,XXX
.25-06, standard, 24" barrel length, SN 62,XXX
.270, 24" barrel length, SN 74,XXX
.30-06,  standard 24" barrel, SN 46,XXX
.458, Custom Sheiland medium wt barrel,  SN 51,XXX


In the short action, L579R, I have the following

.22-250, Heavy Sako barrel, 23.5"  SN 94,XXX
. 22-250, standard barrel, 23.5"  SN  96,XXX
243 (6mm), custom barrel, SN 49,XXX

title: Pre 70 Sako barreled actions
postcontent:
All nine of my Sako barreled actions are "Pre-70"  These are the  premium run of Sakos.  There is a 25% reduction for post '70 Sakos.

In the long action, L61R,  I have the following

.338 mag, magnaported , 24", standard barrel weight,  SN 64,XXX
.25-06, standard, 24" barrel length, SN 62,XXX
.270, 24" barrel length, SN 74,XXX
.30-06,  standard 24" barrel, SN 46,XXX
.458, Custom Sheiland medium wt barrel,  SN 51,XXX


In the short action, L579R, I have the following

.22-250, Heavy Sako barrel, 23.5"  SN 94,XXX
. 22-250, standard barrel, 23.5"  SN  96,XXX
243 (6mm), custom barrel, SN 49,XXX
.308, standard barrel, 23.5", SN 80,XXX

I have not been able to get a professional evaluation on these so far.  The current Blue Book shows complete guns in this range right at $1,000 in 100% condition.  These have no stocks, so, I will go with half price.  You know most stocks are not worth the same  price as the metal.  Well, these have never been mounted, fired, etc.  They are 100%!  So, I think I will set the opening price at $500 for any of them.   I am going to  put them on Gunbroker soon.  Then I will get a good sense of their value.  I am seeing guns that show a certain value bring about 50% more on Gunbroker.  You never know.  Of course, there are far fewer stock makers than gun buyers.
